T1  - Population Aging and Immigration in Japan
AN  - 1907235547
AB  - This article discusses the development of immigration policies in postwar Japan by taking into consideration the long-term socioeconomic and demographic transformations of Japanese society. We demonstrate how Japan is experiencing the tension between the evident need of domestic enterprises for unskilled labor and the stated policies of not admitting foreign unskilled workers. We also point out that by the time Japan is ready to open its door to foreign laborers, particularly those from Asia, many of the Asian developing countries may find themselves in a situation where they have lost their potential to supply labor due to accelerating fertility decline. Finally, we conclude that since the processes shaping international labor migration are extremely complex - which involve economic, political, institutional and social elements - and the conditions in the world are constantly changing, it is virtually impossible to make any definite predictions regarding future international flows of labor into Japan.
